changed that to Ansible and Terraform. However&nbsp;
I’m keeping Puppet and Chef in the course for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:34.280
two reasons. First, notice the wording of the&nbsp;
new exam topic: Recognize the capabilities&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:40.360
of configuration management mechanisms,&nbsp;
“such as” Ansible and Terraform. For me,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:46.160
the words “such as” imply that there could be&nbsp;
others on the exam. Second, Puppet and Chef&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:51.880
help illustrate key concepts, like comparing the&nbsp;
agentless architecture of Ansible and Terraform&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:57.880
to the agent-based architecture of Puppet and&nbsp;
Chef. So instead of modifying the previous video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:03.600
I’m adding this new one to focus on Terraform.
Before we get started, let me take a minute to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:09.800
shill my books, Acing the CCNA Exam volumes&nbsp;
1 and 2. These books cover everything on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:15.720
latest version of the CCNA exam, including the&nbsp;
topics of this video. The very final chapter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:21.840
chapter 25 of volume 2, focuses on Ansible&nbsp;
and Terraform, and also includes a bit about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:27.560
Puppet and Chef. I always recommend using books in&nbsp;
combination with a video course, so if you want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:31.840
get my books, check out the links on the screen&nbsp;
now to buy them directly from the publisher,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:38.200
or find them on Amazon. Now let’s get started.
So, what are we going to cover in this video?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.200 --> 00:01:42.680
Of course, the focus is on Terraform, but&nbsp;
I’ll take the opportunity to introduce a few&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:49.320
new concepts. Specifically, we’ll talk about&nbsp;
the concept of infrastructure as code, IaC;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:54.360
Terraform and the other tools we’ve covered&nbsp;
are examples of IaC. Then we’ll compare&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:59.720
infrastructure provisioning and configuration&nbsp;
management. Whereas Ansible is primarily used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:05.160
for configuration management, Terraform leans&nbsp;
toward provisioning. We’ll then cover the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:11.960
concepts of mutable vs immutable infrastructure,&nbsp;
and procedural vs declarative approaches. Finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:18.200
we’ll shift our focus to Terraform itself&nbsp;
and cover its basics. Okay, let’s begin.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:23.640
First let’s look at the concept of infrastructure&nbsp;
as code. Actually, we’ve already covered it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:28.600
I just didn’t use the specific term in&nbsp;
the last video. Infrastructure as code,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:34.240
IaC, is the practice of provisioning and&nbsp;
managing infrastructure, such as servers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:38.840
networks, and cloud resources, using&nbsp;
machine-readable configuration files,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:45.520
code, instead of manual configuration via&nbsp;
CLI or GUI. That probably sounds familiar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:52.320
because Ansible, Puppet, and Chef are examples of&nbsp;
IaC configuration management tools. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:56.800
Ansible manages device configurations using&nbsp;
several files that are used by the control&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:02.960
node. We covered these in the previous&nbsp;
video. Ansible uses playbook, inventory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:09.040
template, and variable files. Ansible runs on&nbsp;
the control node and uses these files to manage&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:15.880
the infrastructure. Instead of configuring the&nbsp;
devices via the CLI or GUI, their configurations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:21.800
are managed via these code files, hence the&nbsp;
term “infrastructure as code”. Terraform,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:27.280
on the other hand, is an IaC-based provisioning&nbsp;
tool that automates the creation of infrastructure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:32.480
resources. In the next slide I’ll clarify the&nbsp;
difference between configuration management and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:39.120
provisioning, but Terraform is primarily used for&nbsp;
provisioning. So, to summarize, infrastructure as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:44.680
code automates infrastructure deployment and&nbsp;
management, ensuring consistency, scalability,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:52.440
and repeatability. Basically, the various benefits&nbsp;
of automation that we covered in previous videos.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:57.880
So, I mentioned that Ansible, Puppet, and Chef are&nbsp;
primarily configuration management tools, whereas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:03.920
Terraform is primarily a provisioning tool. Let’s&nbsp;
clarify what the difference is. First, what is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:10.280
configuration management? Tools like Ansible,&nbsp;
Puppet, and Chef manage existing infrastructure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:17.320
by installing software, configuring settings, and&nbsp;
maintaining system state. This ensures consistency&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:23.160
by applying and enforcing configurations across&nbsp;
multiple devices. Again, these are the benefits&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:29.160
of Ansible, Puppet, and Chef that I covered&nbsp;
in the previous video. As for infrastructure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:35.440
provisioning, it creates, modifies, and deletes&nbsp;
infrastructure resources such as servers and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:41.160
network infrastructure. For example, creating&nbsp;
virtual servers and routers on a cloud platform&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:48.800
like AWS. But the focus is on initial setup&nbsp;
rather than ongoing configuration management.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.800 --> 00:04:54.880
To summarize, configuration management tools work&nbsp;
on already existing systems, whereas provisioning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:59.640
tools build infrastructure from scratch. Of&nbsp;
course, these tools can be used together.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:06.640
For example, Terraform, a provisioning tool,&nbsp;
and Ansible, a configuration management tool,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:12.400
often work as a pair. Terraform&nbsp;
provisions infrastructure, creating VMs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:17.400
network infrastructure, storage, and other&nbsp;
resources, while Ansible provides ongoing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:22.720
configuration and management, maintaining&nbsp;
those systems. With all of that said,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:28.960
both Terraform and Ansible have some overlap. Each&nbsp;
can perform both provisioning and configuration&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:36.320
management to some extent. But their strengths&nbsp;
are different, so they’re often used together.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:40.880
One major difference between infrastructure&nbsp;
provisioning and management tools is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:46.640
approach they take with the infrastructure:&nbsp;
is the infrastructure mutable or immutable?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:51.720
Configuration management tools typically&nbsp;
use a mutable infrastructure approach. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:57.160
means that infrastructure can be modified after&nbsp;
deployment, such as applying updates, patches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:03.320
or configuration changes. In other words, changes&nbsp;
are made in place, meaning existing resources are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:09.320
updated rather than replaced. This is just like&nbsp;
when you manually modify a device’s configuration&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:15.920
in the CLI. So, when using a mutable approach,&nbsp;
if you want to update the config of this VM,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:22.480
Ansible or a similar tool would simply update the&nbsp;
config while leaving the VM itself in place. Only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:28.480
the relevant settings are changed. So, what’s&nbsp;
the alternative to mutable infrastructure?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:34.440
Provisioning tools like Terraform typically&nbsp;
employ an immutable infrastructure approach.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:40.640
This means that infrastructure cannot be changed&nbsp;
after deployment. So, any changes you make involve&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:46.480
replacing the previous resource with a new one. If&nbsp;
you want to update the configuration of this VM,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:51.080
Terraform or a similar tool would have to&nbsp;
create an updated instance of the VM with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.080 --> 00:06:56.920
the configuration changes applied, and then&nbsp;
destroy the old instance. One benefit of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.920 --> 00:07:02.600
approach is that there is no configuration drift.&nbsp;
Each deployment starts from a fresh, predefined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:08.640
state. There’s no opportunity for individual&nbsp;
changes to accumulate with each configuration.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:13.440
Configuration drift isn’t a major issue when&nbsp;
Ansible or other mutable infrastructure tools&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:21.640
are properly managed. But Terraform’s immutable&nbsp;
approach virtually eliminates the risk altogether

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:26.800
The final concept we’ll cover before focusing&nbsp;
on Terraform itself is the difference between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:32.840
a procedural and declarative approach. Some&nbsp;
tools take a procedural approach to managing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:38.240
infrastructure, also called an imperative&nbsp;
approach. This means that the tool follows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:44.720
explicit steps in a specific order to achieve the&nbsp;
desired outcome. So the user, the engineer using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:51.000
the tool, must define each specific action in the&nbsp;
correct order to configure the infrastructure.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.720
This provides greater control than the declarative&nbsp;
approach we’ll cover next, but is more demanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.720 --> 00:08:01.640
on the user. They have to know exactly which steps&nbsp;
are required to achieve their desired end result,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:07.320
and in which order those steps should be&nbsp;
executed. Then there is the declarative approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:13.040
which defines the desired end state instead&nbsp;
of the specific steps. The tool itself,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:19.440
such as Terraform, figures out the steps needed to&nbsp;
achieve the goal. This makes it easier to maintain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:24.560
and ensure consistency across deployments because&nbsp;
the user doesn’t have to worry about ordering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:29.760
individual commands and configurations on each&nbsp;
platform. They only have to think about defining&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:36.040
what they want the final result to be. So, to&nbsp;
summarize, A procedural approach focuses on how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.040 --> 00:08:42.200
to make changes with explicit steps. For example,&nbsp;
when configuring a new router, configure the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:50.360
router’s hostname with HOSTNAME R1. Configure the&nbsp;
IP address of G0/1 with the IP ADDRESS command.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:56.680
Enable the interface with NO SHUTDOWN, , and&nbsp;
so on. These are the specific configurations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.680 --> 00:09:03.000
needed on a Cisco router, and the steps would be&nbsp;
different if it was a Juniper router, for example.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:08.800
A declarative approach, on the other hand, focuses&nbsp;
on what the final state should be. You can tell&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:17.080
Terraform “Create a router named R1 with IP&nbsp;
address 192.168.1.1/24 on its G0/1 interface,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:22.440
ensuring the interface is enabled”. Terraform&nbsp;
should then figure out the necessary steps to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.440 --> 00:09:28.160
achieve that end state. So, I’ve mentioned&nbsp;
that Terraform uses a declarative approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:33.840
but you’re probably wondering about the others.&nbsp;
Here’s a table. I’ve categorized Ansible and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:38.920
Chef as procedural, but it’s worth noting that&nbsp;
they do have some declarative elements as well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:44.200
especially Ansible. People who use Ansible&nbsp;
a lot might get angry at me for categorizing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:49.960
Ansible as procedural. But Red Hat, the&nbsp;
company that owns and develops Ansible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:55.160
also says it is procedural, so for your CCNA&nbsp;
studies I’d say it’s best to consider Ansible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.160 --> 00:10:00.480
a procedural tool. Meanwhile, Terraform&nbsp;
and Puppet use a declarative approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:08.440
allowing you to define the desired end state&nbsp;
and let the tool figure out the rest for you.

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:14.560
Finally let’s move on to Terraform, which is an&nbsp;
open-source IaC tool developed by HashiCorp, an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:21.400
American company that was acquired by IBM in 2025.&nbsp;
As I’ve mentioned a few times, it is primarily&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:26.440
a provisioning tool, focused on deploying&nbsp;
infrastructure resources on various cloud and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:33.800
on-prem platforms. In Terraform, these platforms&nbsp;
are called providers and include AWS, Azure,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:41.680
GCP, Kubernetes, and many more; it supports over&nbsp;
1000 different providers. For CCNA students, this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:47.880
includes integrations with Cisco platforms like&nbsp;
Catalyst Center, ACI, which is Application Centric&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:54.840
Infrastructure, Cisco’s data center SDN solution.&nbsp;
And IOS XE, which is the type of IOS you’ll find&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.840 --> 00:11:02.080
on modern Cisco devices like Catalyst switches.&nbsp;
Like Ansible, Terraform uses a push model and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:09.400
is agentless. It doesn’t require a software agent&nbsp;
on infrastructure it provisions or manages. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:15.160
now let’s see how Terraform actually works. At&nbsp;
the core of Terraform is Terraform Core; this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:21.120
the main Terraform software, typically running on&nbsp;
a Linux server, that processes configurations and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:21.120 --> 00:11:27.320
interacts with providers. An engineer creates&nbsp;
Terraform configuration files, which specify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:33.320
the desired end state in a declarative fashion.&nbsp;
It’s up to Terraform Core to take that desired&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:39.480
end state and deploy the necessary infrastructure&nbsp;
on the appropriate provider or providers, such as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:47.680
deploying cloud resources on AWS. It does this via&nbsp;
each provider’s APIs. And one more key element is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.680 --> 00:11:53.960
the state file, which Terraform uses to track the&nbsp;
state of the deployed infrastructure. By comparing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:58.080
the current state of the infrastructure&nbsp;
to the desired end state defined in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:03.960
configuration files, Terraform can identify which&nbsp;
actions it needs to take, and in which order,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:09.800
to achieve the desired result. To summarize,&nbsp;
these are Terraform’s four key components,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:15.840
all working together to provision and manage&nbsp;
infrastructure: Terraform Core, the core software&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:21.800
developed by HashiCorp. Configuration files,&nbsp;
which an engineer creates to define the desired&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:27.080
end state of the infrastructure. The state&nbsp;
file, which tracks the current state of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:35.400
deployed infrastructure. And the providers, the&nbsp;
platforms on which the infrastructure is deployed.

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:41.680
Let’s cover a few more key points about Terraform.&nbsp;
The basic Terraform workflow consists of three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:46.600
main steps. The first is “write”, in&nbsp;
which you define the desired end state&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:53.520
of your infrastructure resources in configuration&nbsp;
files. The second step is “plan,” where Terraform&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:58.960
analyzes your configuration files and shows you&nbsp;
exactly what changes will be made. This lets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:05.080
you review and confirm the changes before applying&nbsp;
them. And the third step is apply, where Terraform&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:10.760
executes the plan to provision and manage the&nbsp;
infrastructure resources. That’s basically how it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:17.680
works. If you think back to Ansible, hopefully you&nbsp;
remember that Ansible itself is written in Python,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:24.080
while its playbooks are written in YAML. So&nbsp;
what about Terraform? While Terraform Core is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:29.200
written in Go, the configuration files that&nbsp;
define the desired end state are written in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:37.160
HashiCorp Configuration Language, HCL. HCL is&nbsp;
an example of a domain-specific language, DSL,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:42.040
which is specialized for a particular purpose,&nbsp;
like Puppet’s DSL mentioned in the previous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.040 --> 00:13:49.200
video. Since DSLs are designed for specific&nbsp;
tasks, they make complex operations simpler,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:53.400
and they require less effort compared to&nbsp;
general-purpose languages like Python or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:59.920
Go. The downside is that HCL is another thing&nbsp;
you have to learn specifically to use Terraform,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:05.160
but it’s relatively simple compared to learning&nbsp;
a full programming language. So, the key points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:11.400
to remember here are the three steps of the&nbsp;
Terraform workflow: write, plan, and apply.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:16.720
And also remember that Terraform Core is written&nbsp;
in Go, while the configuration files you make are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:25.200
written in HashiCorp Configuration Language,&nbsp;
HCL, which is a Domain Specific Language.

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:30.280
Okay, those are the basics of Terraform. Now&nbsp;
here’s a one-slide summary before we move on to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:36.480
the quiz. Infrastructure as Code is the practice&nbsp;
of provisioning and managing infrastructure using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:41.920
machine-readable configuration files instead&nbsp;
of manual configuration. Ansible, Puppet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.920 --> 00:14:48.360
Chef, and Terraform are all examples of IaC&nbsp;
tools. But not all IaC tools are used for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:54.600
exact same purpose. Configuration management&nbsp;
tools like Ansible, Puppet, and Chef focus on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.600 --> 00:15:00.120
managing existing infrastructure, doing things&nbsp;
like installing software, configuring settings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.120 --> 00:15:05.560
and generally maintaining the state of your&nbsp;
systems. Infrastructure provisioning tools like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:12.120
Terraform, on the other hand, focus on creating,&nbsp;
modifying, and deleting infrastructure resources.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:17.360
That doesn’t mean that Ansible can’t be used to&nbsp;
provision resources or Terraform can’t be used to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:24.120
make configuration changes, it’s just that each&nbsp;
tool is better fit for a different purpose. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.120 --> 00:15:29.000
then covered mutable infrastructure, which means&nbsp;
that the infrastructure can be modified after&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:35.720
deployment. And immutable infrastructure, meaning&nbsp;
that it cannot be changed after deployment. Any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:40.840
changes involve replacing the previous resource&nbsp;
with a new, updated version, and then deleting the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:47.080
old one. Provisioning tools like Terraform use an&nbsp;
immutable approach, whereas management tools like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:47.080 --> 00:15:53.480
Ansible use a mutable approach to infrastructure.&nbsp;
We then compared the procedural and declarative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:53.480 --> 00:16:00.040
approaches. A procedural, also called imperative,&nbsp;
approach follows explicit steps in a specific&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:05.600
order to achieve the desired outcome, and these&nbsp;
steps must be specified by the engineer using the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:12.720
tool. A declarative approach defines the desired&nbsp;
end state, and the IaC tool, such as Terraform,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:18.880
figures out the steps needed to achieve that goal,&nbsp;
and in which order they should be executed. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:25.920
finally we looked at Terraform itself, it’s an&nbsp;
open-source IaC tool developed by HashiCorp. It’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:31.920
primarily a provisioning tool used for deploying&nbsp;
infrastructure on providers like AWS, Azure,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:31.920 --> 00:16:40.000
GCP, Kubernetes, etc. Terraform interacts with&nbsp;
these providers via their APIs. Like Ansible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:47.040
it uses a push model and is agentless. Its main&nbsp;
components are Terraform Core, the configuration&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.040 --> 00:16:52.000
files where you specify the desired end state,&nbsp;
the state file that tracks the current state of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:59.040
the infrastructure, and the providers. The basic&nbsp;
workflow consists of three main steps: write,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:05.200
plan, and apply. You could also add a fourth step&nbsp;
there: destroy, in which you delete the resources&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:11.280
after they are no longer needed. But these three&nbsp;
are considered the main steps. Terraform Core is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:16.400
written in Go, and the configuration files are&nbsp;
written in HashiCorp Configuration Language,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:21.880
which is a domain-specific language. Alright,&nbsp;
that’s what we covered in this video. Just a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:26.280
very high-level overview of Terraform, but&nbsp;
as long as you know these basics you should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.280 --> 00:17:34.600
be ready for the CCNA exam. Now let’s do&nbsp;
a short quiz to test your understanding.

00:17:34.600 --> 00:17:38.640
Here’s quiz question 1. Which of&nbsp;
the following are characteristics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:47.920
of Terraform? (select two) Pause the&nbsp;
video now to think about your answers.

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:53.720
Okay, the answers are B, declarative, and&nbsp;
C, immutable infrastructure. Terraform&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:58.160
uses a declarative approach in which&nbsp;
you specify the desired end state and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:03.360
Terraform takes care of the rest for you.&nbsp;
It also uses immutable infrastructure,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:09.280
where a particular resource can’t be changed after&nbsp;
provisioning. To change a resource, Terraform will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:17.040
deploy a new version of the resource and then&nbsp;
delete the old one instead. Okay, next question.

00:18:17.040 --> 00:18:21.880
Here’s question 2. What are the three&nbsp;
main steps of the Terraform workflow?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:28.760
Pause the video now to think about your answer.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:35.520
Okay, the answer is D, write, plan, apply. In&nbsp;
the write step, you define the desired state of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:41.080
your infrastructure in configuration files. In&nbsp;
the plan step you verify the changes that will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:46.920
be executed before applying them. And then&nbsp;
in apply, Terraform applies whatever changes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.920 --> 00:18:54.640
necessary to bring the infrastructure in line with&nbsp;
the desired state. Now let’s do one more question.

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:59.480
Here’s quiz question 3. Which of the&nbsp;
following IaC tools are focused on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:09.800
configuration management? Select three. Pause&nbsp;
the video now to think about your answers.

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:13.680
Okay, the answers are A, C, and D. Ansible, Chef,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:18.960
and Puppet are primarily used for configuration&nbsp;
management, whereas Terraform is a provisioning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.960 --> 00:19:24.360
tool. To take advantage of the strengths of&nbsp;
each, it’s fairly common to use a combination,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.360 --> 00:19:31.040
such as Terraform and Ansible. These tools&nbsp;
aren’t exclusive and can be used together.

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:35.520
Okay, that’s all for this video. We covered some&nbsp;
additional concepts related to Infrastructure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:39.080
as Code that weren’t covered in the&nbsp;
previous video, and then focused on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:45.120
the basics of Terraform, a very popular&nbsp;
IaC provisioning tool. For the CCNA exam,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.120 --> 00:19:49.280
I recommend knowing the basics of Terraform&nbsp;
